            <div>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>The inclosed will do your business about the picture at <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0168">Dunrobin castle</placeName>.<note resp="editor">At
                            <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0167">Golspie, Sutherland</placeName>, in the
                            <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0711">Scottish Highlands</placeName>. Pennant
                        visited it in 1769, and gives a description of the paintings which he saw
                        there in <bibl type="editorial">Thomas Pennant, <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0001">
                                <hi rend="superscript">A tour in Scotland.
                                MDCCLXIX</hi>
                            </title> (Chester: John Monk, MDCCLXXI [1771])</bibl>
                        [ABBREVIATION], p. 145â€“6.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I again surveyed <rs type="art" ref="ardb.xml#ar0004">Lady Desmonds picture</rs>
                    last year &amp; I plainly saw it was no <persName ref="pe0314">Rembrandt</persName> which I knew was impossible when I looked into his
                        life.<note resp="editor">Bull was much exercised by a print of <persName ref="pe0315">Catherine, Countess of Desmond</persName>, a
                        reputed centenarian living in the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries, which
                        he found engraved from a painting in a Scottish collection in April 1773.
                        Horace Walpole reported that on the reverse of a copy of the picture at
                        Windsor it was described as 'The Mother of Rembrandt', but Pennant refuted
                        this (as did James Granger) and had the picture engraved for the third
                        edition of his <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0004">
                                <hi rend="superscript">A tour in Scotland. MDCCLXIX</hi>
                            </title>
                            (Warrington, 1774)</bibl>, p. 74. <persName ref="pe0313">Richard Bull</persName> eventually conceded that the portrait was
                        indeed by <persName ref="pe0314">Rembrandt</persName>, and bore no
                        real relation to the <persName ref="pe0315">Catherine, Countess of
                            Desmond</persName>. Peltz, 'Bull-Granger Letterbook', pp. 13t14, 115,
                        117, 123, 124; <persName ref="pe0232">Thomas Pennant</persName> to
                            <persName ref="pe0316">James Granger</persName>, 21 October
                        1774, Malcolm, p. 157.</note> always ready to execute y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> commands I am D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                    Sir</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> most obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0001">Downing</placeName> June 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1773.</dateline>
